05731nam a22007935i 9781477309292DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212016txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016004934  a97814773092927 a10.7560/3092852doi  a(DE-B1597)586917  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aE175.8b.P735 2016 4aE175.8b.P735 2016 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a973.071/122300aPracticing Transnationalism :bAmerican Studies in the Middle East /ced. by Edward J. Lundy, Eileen T. Lundy. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Questions and Challenges -- t1. The American Question -- t2. The Politics of American-Style Higher Education in the Middle East -- tPart II. Contexts and Implications -- t3. The American Liberal Education System and Its Development at the American University of Beirut -- t4. Shifting the Gorilla: The Failure of the American Unipolar in the Middle East -- t5. Discourse, Palestine, and the Authoritative News Media -- tPart III. Cultural Encounters -- t6. Arabic Poetry in America -- t7. The Stones We Throw Are Rhymes: Imagining America in Palestinian Hip-Hop -- tPart IV. Classroom Encounters -- t8. American Studies in the Arabian Gulf: Teaching American Politics in Bahrain -- t9. Waiting for Hasan: Lewis Hine, Service Learning, and the Practical Pedagogy of American Studies -- t10. Teaching in the Middle East: Partial Cosmopolitanism -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first decade of the twenty-first century, American studies programs began to spread in the Middle East. During a time of rising anti-American sentiment, ten major programs were established in the region. What impulses propelled universities in the Middle East to establish these centers and programs? What motivated students to take courses and pursue degrees in American studies? In part, American studies programs developed as a way to “know the enemy,” to better understand America’s ubiquitous influence in foreign relations, technology, and culture; however, some programs grew because residents admired the ideals set forth as American, including democracy and free speech. Practicing Transnationalism investigates these issues and others, using the experiences and research of the editors and contributors, who worked either directly in these programs or as adjunct to them. These scholars seek to understand what American power means to people in the Middle East. They examine the challenge of developing American studies programs in a transnational paradigm, striving to build programs that are separate from and critical of American imperialism without simply becoming anti-American. In the essays, the contributors provide context for how the field of American studies has grown and developed, and they offer views of cultural interactions and classroom situations, demonstrating the problems instructors faced and how they worked to address them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aEducation, HigherzMiddle East. 0aEducational exchangeszMiddle East. 0aTransnationalism. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Betty S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavell, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElayyan, Hani Ismail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLucas, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLundy, Edward J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLundy, Edward J., eedit